Compound of Fuchs ("fox") + Teufel ("devil") + -s- (fugenmorphem) + wild ("wild, untamed, ferocious, savage"). In the German dictionary of the Brothers Grimm, the adjective is used to mean "so upset, as if one were completely devilish, in the highest degree upset". The expression is therefore stronger than fuchswild (alreday circulating since the 16th century). R. Becker thought of a connection of "fuchsen" with the old word "ficken" which means "to drive back and forth briefly and quickly, to strike, to whip". The PONS dictionary, on the other hand, sees the struggling trapped fox, which may have been infected with rabies, as the origin of the word fuchswild, which originated in the Tyrol and was later emotionally reinforced by the addition of the devil and became a figure of speech. In the Digital Dictionary of the German Language of the 20th century, "fuchsteufelswild" is summarised according to Pfeiffer's etymological dictionary as: "'very angry' (18th century); fuchs- has a reinforcing function as in older fuchswild (16th century)".

Compound of the adjective inner ("internal, inner") + Schwein ("pig") + Hund ("dog"). The word Schweinehund (pig dog) is already known in the student language of the 19th century as a coarse swear word and goes back to the sow dog used for hunting wild boar ("Sauhund") . The tasks of the latter, such as rushing, tiring and holding on, were transferred to the character traits of biting people. The word exists only in German, Swedish (svinhund) and Russian (свинособака) and cannot be translated literally.

The first, by Frank Vigor Morley in 1947, says it is a term used in chess to indicate winning by use of the glutei muscles--the habit of remaining stolid in one's seat hour by hour, making moves that are sound but uninspired, until one's opponent blunders through boredom. Univerbation of the phrase Zeche ("bill") prellen ("to cheat/to bounce") with the derivative morpheme -er for agent. The corresponding word for the crime, "Zechprellerei", has been used since the 19th century. It is made up of "Zeche" and "bounce". Zeche in the sense of tavern bill has been documented since the 15th century. It has developed from the late Middle High German meaning "contribution to the common revelry of a society". "Prellen" originally means "to push, to hit, to fling up". The additional meaning "to cheat" derives from a hunting custom of the 17th and 18th centuries in which a fox was repeatedly flung up on a tightly stretched cloth and thus bounced out of its freedom just for the "amusement of hunting parties".
